ce:section.ce:para:
In conclusion, the present work demonstrates a facile and green strategy to fabricate thiol-functionalized LDH as a novel type of adsorbent for highly selective removal of metal ions. In this study, the N,S-CDs-LDH composites were successfully synthesized via direct assembly of N,S-CDs on the surface of LDH. The preparation of N,S-CDs-LDH nanocomposite was relatively simple, rapid, environmental-friendly, cost-effective and an energy efficient route to a novel type of adsorbent for removing heavy metals on the basis of the LDH-based materials. Based on the soft Lewis base nature of the sulfide ions in N,S-CDs, the N,S-CDs-LDH material exhibits substantial removal characteristics and excellent selectivity for a variety of soft Lewis acid heavy metal ions. Investigating the adsorption behavior toward different metal ions showed that, in a solution containing a mixture of the all of six metal ions, the selectivity order of Ag+, Hg2+>Cu2+>>>Pb2+ > Zn2+>Cd2+ can be observed. In a solution containing mixtures of the three ions of Hg2+, Ag+ and Cu2+, the selectivity order of Ag+>>Hg2+>>>Cu2+ was observed using N,S-CDs-LDH as a limiting reagent. On the other hand, the presence of functional amine groups on CDs can improve the adsorption capacity. The N,S-CDs-LDH exhibited a high affinity (Kd
                     ) of 9.9 × 106 mL g−1 (Hg2+) and 2.0 × 107 mL g−1 (Ag+). Also a significant adsorption capacity (qm
                     ) of 625.0 and 714.3 mg g−1 were obtained for Hg2+ and Ag+ removal from aqueous solutions, respectively. This type of chemistry is unique and important in the selective recovery of precious metals such as Ag+ or the removal of toxic heavy metals such as Hg2+ from mining and waste waters. Based on XRD results, after the removal of heavy metal ions, the N,S-CDs-LDH keep their original crystallite shape, indicating the good chemical stability of the sorbent.
